Glucose Monitoring System is a device that continuously tracks blood glucose levels in diabetic patients through sensors placed under the skin.</p><p><b>2. How does an Implantable CGM work?</b><br>An Implantable CGM works by inserting a sensor under the skin, which measures glucose levels in the interstitial fluid and transmits the data to a monitoring device.</p><p><b>3. Is Implantable CGM suitable for children?</b><br>Yes, Implantable CGMs are designed to be used in children with diabetes, providing continuous glucose monitoring and better management of blood sugar levels.</p><p><b>4. How long does an Implantable CGM sensor last?</b><br>Implantable CGM sensors typically last for several months, with newer models offering extended wear times for more convenient monitoring.</p><p><b>5. What are the benefits of Implantable CGMs over traditional blood glucose monitoring?</b><br>Implantable CGMs offer continuous, real-time glucose readings, eliminating the need for frequent finger-prick testing and providing more detailed data for diabetes management.</p><p><b>6. Can Implantable CGMs help prevent diabetes complications?</b><br>Yes, by providing continuous glucose data, Implantable CGMs help prevent the long-term complications of diabetes by ensuring better glucose control and more timely interventions.</p><p><b>7. Are Implantable CGMs painful to use?</b><br>Implantable CGMs are designed for minimal discomfort, with sensors being implanted under the skin with local anesthesia, ensuring a low-pain experience for most patients.</p><p><b>8. What is the cost of an Implantable Continuous Glucose Monitoring System?</b><br>The cost of an Implantable CGM system varies depending on the brand, region, and specific features, but it generally ranges from several hundred to a few thousand dollars.</p><p><b>9. How do Implantable CGMs improve diabetes management for adults?</b><br>For adults, Implantable CGMs provide continuous glucose monitoring, helping them better manage their bloo